additional_comments: Leveraging technology is good, but as actuaries, we also need to promote understanding.  For example, our organization uses a skills based excel test to screen new actuarial applicants with several exams and are very often disappointed to see that most applicants do not spot the severe, but realistic, data issues we inserted as a "test" of their understanding.  Some have even come up with negative answers to a regression analysis without understanding that a negative answer to the question we ask is impossible!!  Technology itself is only a tool, and data quality and understanding related to the real world cannot be overlooked as work is automated and models are developed!  How much is data quality analysis built into model creation and usage?  (Should be there in abundance!!)

additional_comments: I work in a commercial lines analytics role.  Most of my day-to-day data querying and construction of variables/datasets is done in SAS.  —-  Excel is used for some analysis and for answering most adhoc questions. It continues to be a very useful tool to quickly answer questions or perform steps in a project that don’t require complex dataset manipulation.  —-  Pricing models are done as GLMs in Emblem software. Emblem is also used for building non-pricing GLMs, but those are usually implemented in SAS/R/Python utilizing the variable selections, groups, and variate bins developed in Emblem.  —-  Clustering, simulation, and latent semantic analysis have been primarily worked on in R.  —-   Machine learning models (primarily gradient-boosting methods) are worked on in Python by data scientist(s) on the team and I have peer reviewed/validated.  —-  Tableau is used for most data visualization cases, and in some projects the end product is a Tableau dashboard.

Short Answer: Alteryx, Access, @Risk, Crystal Ball, Emblem, ResQ  Long Answer: My company uses Alteryx daily for our data preparation (ETL) and analysis, as well as for cool API integrations and even business intelligence purposes. Alteryx makes data very easy to play with, unlike SQL, R, and other programs listed. My fiancé (who supports actuaries on the SOA side) uses DataIku for data preparation and analysis. additional_comments: I'm sure there are lots of valuable tools that we should be using.  Finding the time to learn them and integrate them into our work is the key challenge.  I would love to use new technologies.  It's just often a lot of work to not only learn but to figure out how to adapt existing processes to the new platform.

If new tech is an object of interest, that is one thing, but when 'new' tends toward obsession, it is misguided. I remember when I was first starting in actuarial science, and having had a physics baccalaureate, when studying for exam P I investigated quantum probability models. I also remember attending seminars a few years ago when interest in InsureTech peaked. So I get the excitement. But what excites isn't necessarily what gets the work done. Take Power BI. Some departments in our company are trying to force ways to use Power BI now because it's trendy, even though there is little room for it in their workflow and it actually reduces productivity due to that.     Avant-garde tech and tried-and-true tech aren't equivalent. For actuarial purposes, one requires some tool to import and/or process data. Then one needs tools to manipulate it, and then something to present it. To a surprisingly broad extent of my business's purposes, Excel seems to work just fine still - at least in the manipulation department. I realize that it's 1990s tech, but it's a lingua franca of sorts throughout the field because of its enduring presence. Sure, you can't look cool to your peers if you're an Excel whiz anymore, but actuarial science isn't cool and isn't supposed to be.     In sum tools that can churn data and push it into formats that Excel can work with are valuable, and they keep the industry standardized.

Actuaries are not computer programmers, and proper code review seems to be a huge hole in the expertise of people who have started coding out of a necessity as opposed to being on a team that is experts in code review. There are many resources for learning R, but as far as I can tell, limited resources for ensuring that all code is reasonability checked and that the assumptions are clear. I would recommend a seminar on "code review for actuaries."

new_tech_to_adopt: Some SaaS (Software as a Service) software is used fairly widely in the insurance world and may be expanding. For example, Akur8 and Emblem are modeling tools being used at various companies across the industry.     Building in-house tools is effective, but not feasible for every carrier. Additionally, the upkeep required is extensive and often an unanticipated cost for insurers. In-house tools also bring forth key-person risk.     As machine learning becomes more popular in the industry, SaaS solutions for actuarial applications will likely become more popular. Even if it is not widely used on this survey, I would anticipate it growing in future years.

new_tech_to_adopt: You don't specifically mention either Gradient Boosting or Random Forests.  The term Deep Learning is so ambiguous as to be worthless in a survey. You should explicitly mention Neural Networks too. Also, time series and/or Linear Models have a wide range of potential models and being specific would help in generating a useful survey.  For example, you could mention General Additive Models as a subcategory of GLMs or include a general statement about penalized regression which I think is the most promising path to linking credibility concepts to GLMs for class plan work that I have seen in recent times.
